Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /ˈko.kʷoː/, [ˈkɔ.kʷoː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /ˈko.kwo/, [ˈkɔː.kwɔ]

Etymology 1[edit]

From earlier *quoquō, from Proto-Italic *kʷekʷō, from Proto-Indo-European *pékʷeti by p-kʷ assimilation (compare quīnque, from *pénkʷe), from *pekʷ- (“to cook, become ripe”).

Cognate with Sanskrit पचति (pácati), Avestan 𐬞𐬀𐬗𐬀𐬌𐬙𐬌‎ (pačaiti), Ancient Greek πέσσω (péssō), Tocharian B päk-, Albanian pjek.

Verb[edit]

coquō (present infinitive coquere, perfect active coxī, supine coctum); third conjugation

  1. (transitive) I cook; I prepare food.
  2. (transitive) I ripen.
  3. (transitive) I roast, I dry.

Etymology 2[edit]

Noun[edit]

coquō

  1. dative singular of coquus
  2. ablative singular of coquus
